# Error Handling

## Backend

### HTTP exceptions — use NestJS built-ins
```ts
throw new BadRequestException('message');       // 400
throw new NotFoundException('message');          // 404
throw new InternalServerErrorException('msg');   // 500
throw new HttpException(body, HttpStatus.I_AM_A_TEAPOT); // 418
```

### Never throw raw Error in controllers or services
- Always use NestJS `HttpException` subclasses so `AllExceptionsFilter` can normalise the response

### AllExceptionsFilter response shape
```ts
{
  statusCode: number,
  message: string,
  error: string,       // HTTP status name e.g. "BAD_REQUEST"
  path: string,
  timestamp: string    // ISO 8601
}
```

### HTTP 418 teapot — special case
- The filter passes the body through verbatim — do not wrap in the standard error shape
- Body must include `{ signal: 42, message: "I'm a teapot" }`

### Logging on errors
- `warn` for expected failures (validation, 400s)
- `error` for unexpected failures (500s, unhandled exceptions)
- Always include `{ scenarioId, scenarioType, error: err.message }` in the log context

### Sentry on errors
- Call `SentryService.captureException()` only for 500-level errors
- Call `SentryService.addBreadcrumb()` for 400-level errors

## Frontend

### API error handling
- `ApiError` (from `lib/api.ts`) carries `status` and `message`
- In `useMutation.onError`: distinguish expected errors (400/418/500 from known scenarios) from unexpected ones
- Show `toast` with `variant: 'destructive'` only for truly unexpected errors

### Never swallow errors silently
```ts
// ❌ bad
try { ... } catch (_) {}

// ✅ good
try { ... } catch (err) {
  toast({ title: 'Something went wrong', description: err instanceof Error ? err.message : 'Unknown error' });
}
```

### Loading states
- Always show a loading indicator during async operations
- Use `Skeleton` component for initial data loads
- Use `Loader2` spinner on buttons during mutations (`disabled` + `animate-spin`)

### Empty states
- Every list component must handle the empty case explicitly — never render an empty `<div>`
